.TH "run\-one" "1" "May 28, 2026" "Version 1.0.6" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
\f[B]run\-one\f[R] \- a wrapper utility that prevents concurrent
execution of a command by ensuring only a single instance runs at any
given time
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]run\-one\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]]...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]]...
.PP
\f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]]...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
This utility prevents multiple instances of the same command from
running concurrently.
It can either block a new instance from starting if one is already
active (\f[B]run\-one\f[R]), or terminate the existing process and let
the new one take over (the \f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] variant).
.PP
To ensure only one instance runs at a time, this utility uses a
flock\-based semaphore.
The unique ID for the lock is either specified on the command line using
the \f[B]\-i\f[R] parameter or generated automatically by hashing the
user command line.
The semaphore file is stored in one of the following directories in this
order of preference:
.IP
.EX
$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/one\-run
/run/user/$UID/one\-run
/dev/shm/one\-run_$UID
/tmp/one\-run_$UID
.EE
.PP
Most of these directories are on \f[B]tmpfs\f[R] file systems (/tmp is
often a \f[B]tmpfs\f[R] mount in many recent Linux distributions), and
all of them get cleaned up upon reboot.
.PP
The user supplied command line is then launched with a flock.
If the corresponding lock file is available, then the command gets
launched.
If the lock on the file was already acquired by another process then
depending on the flavor of command
(\f[B]run\-one\f[R]/\f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R]) or use of options
\f[B]\-t\f[R]|\f[B]\-k\f[R], the utility either exits or attempts to
terminate other command instances, waiting for the lock to be released
so that the user command can be launched.
.PP
Lock aquisition wait time can be limited with \f[B]\-w\f[R].
If the lock is not aquired withing that time, the utility can be told to
send \f[B]SIGTERM\f[R] signal for \f[B]\-t\f[R] number of seconds while
probing the lock.
If the lock is still inavailable, the utility can send \f[B]SIGKILL\f[R]
for \f[B]\-k\f[R] number of seconds.
If the process that holds the lock is still active and the lock is not
released, the utility can forcefully invalidate that lock with
\f[B]\-a\f[R] and launch the command regardless.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-w SECONDS\f[R]
maximum time (in seconds) to wait for the lock to become available
before giving up on acquiring the lock or start sending
\f[B]TERM\f[R]/\f[B]KILL\f[R] signals; only whole numbers are
understood, decimals are not allowed
.TP
\f[B]\-t SECONDS\f[R]
after the wait period \f[B]\-w\f[R] expires, keep sending
\f[B]SIGTERM\f[R] signal for this number of seconds, while checking
whether the semaphore lock is released.
Launches the command if the lock becomes available.
.PP
\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
Running \f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] is equivalent to running \f[B]run\-one
\-t 600\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-k SECONDS\f[R]
after both the \f[B]\-w\f[R] and \f[B]\-t\f[R] expire, keep sending
\f[B]SIGKILL\f[R] signal for this number of seconds, while checking
whether the semaphore lock is released.
Launches the command if the lock becomes available.
.TP
\f[B]\-a\f[R]
run this invocation anyway, even if another process does not give up the
lock in the time given by \f[B]\-w\f[R] or \f[B]\-t\f[R] or
\f[B]\-k\f[R].
This invalidates the lock acquired by another process and creates a new
lock file
.TP
\f[B]\-i TOKEN\f[R]
use this token for the lock file name instead of calculating user
command hash.
This option is also used internally when running \f[B]keep\-one\-running
cmd\f[R], as this command variant internally runs as \f[B]run\-one +
keep\-running + cmd\f[R] as \f[B]run\-one\f[R] needs the token for
\f[B]cmd\f[R] and not for \f[B]keep\-running + cmd\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-T\f[R]
does not run the command but locates other instances of the command and
prints the process IDs of the processes holding the lock
.TP
\f[B]\-\-\f[R]
double\-dash can (optionally) be used to separate the options from the
user command.
.TP
\f[B]\-E EXIT_CODE\f[R]
custom error exit code; enables the user to differentiate between the
command failure and the utility exit error (see EXIT STATUS section for
details)
.TP
\f[B]\-D PATH\f[R]
debug/log file path
.TP
\f[B]\-h | \-\-help\f[R]
Print help information
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
run\-this\-one inotifywait \-m \(ti/tmp \-e close_write | \(rs
    run\-until\-failure sh \-c \(aqread \-r event && echo \(dq$event\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
Sets a watcher on \(ti/tmp directory and keeps printing events that
occur whenever a new file is written in it.
If another identical instance of such watcher was already running, it
gets terminated prior to running this instance.
.IP
.EX
run\-one \-w 60 \-t 30 \-k 10 \-a \-i \(dqWatch my DIR\(dq \-\- inotifywait \-m \(ti/tmp \-e close_write | \(rs
    keep\-running \-u f \-r 100 \-\- sh \-c \(aqread \-r event && echo \(dq$event\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
Similar to the previous example but has more control.
First \f[B]\-w 60\f[R] it allows 1 min for the other process to finish,
then sends \f[B]SIGTERM\f[R] to another instance for 30 sec \f[B]\-t
30\f[R] asking it to wrap it up, and then attempts to shoot it with
SIGKILL for 10 sec \f[B]\-k 10\f[R].
It searches the other instance by \(lqWatch my DIR\(rq token (the other
instance must be launched with \f[B]run\-one \-i \(lqWatch my
DIR\(rq\f[R]).
The \f[B]keep\-running\f[R] pipe runs until either the user command
fails or until it quits 100 times.
.SH EXIT STATUS
\f[B]run\-one\f[R] and \f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] exit with one of the
following status:
.IP
.EX
0     upon success
122   when this utility encounters a problem; customizable with \-E
.EE
.PP
Exit code 122 is returned the utility itself encounters an abnormal
situation, e.g.\ when a parameter is invalid of flock fails.
This code is customizable with \-E option.
.PP
Any other exit code indicates the status returned from the user command.
